'''Koyasu Jizō-ji''' (子安地蔵寺) is a {{ill|Shingon Buddhist temple|ja|寺院|qq=draft}} of the {{ill|Kōyasan Shingon-shū|ja|高野山真言宗|qq=draft}} sect, located in {{ill|Hashimoto, Wakayama|ja|和歌山県橋本市|qq=draft}}. Its {{ill|Mountain name (sangō)|ja|山号|qq=draft}} is *Isan-zan* (易産山), and its principal image is {{ill|Jizō Bosatsu|ja|地蔵菩薩|qq=draft}}. The temple’s formal name is *Isan-zan Gokoku-in Jizō-ji* (易産山護国院地蔵寺), while *Koyasu Jizō-ji* is a commonly used name. It is well known for its wisteria flowers.

== History ==

The temple was founded in the spring of {{ill|Tenpyō 9|ja|天平9th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|737 AD|ja|737th year|qq=draft}}) by {{ill|Gyōki|ja|行基|qq=draft}}. The temple’s principal image, a statue of {{ill|Jizō Bosatsu|ja|地蔵菩薩|qq=draft}}, is said to have been carved by Gyōki himself and is known as the "Most Victorious and Oldest Jizō Bosatsu in Japan." This Jizō was enshrined at the temple to provide prayers for safe childbirth, leading to its name *Koyasu Jizō* (子安地蔵).<ref name="temple_history">[https://hananotera.com/history History of Koyasu Jizō-ji]</ref>

In {{ill|Tenshō 9|ja|天正9th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|1581 AD|ja|1581st year|qq=draft}}), during the {{ill|Kōyasan Campaign|ja|高野山攻め|qq=draft}} led by {{ill|Oda Nobunaga|ja|織田信長|qq=draft}} and his son {{ill|Oda Nobutaka|ja|織田信孝|qq=draft}}, the temple was set ablaze, and all its structures were destroyed. However, the principal image was hidden deep in the mountains and later discovered by villagers. The location where it was hidden is still known today as *Kakuregata* (かくれがた).<ref name="temple_history"/>

During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft}}, the temple gained significant patronage from {{ill|Tokugawa Yorinobu|ja|徳川頼宣|qq=draft}}, lord of the {{ill|Kishū Domain|ja|紀州藩|qq=draft}}, after it was said to have helped his daughter through a difficult childbirth. Koyasu Jizō-ji subsequently became the official prayer temple for safe childbirth for the {{ill|Kishū Tokugawa family|ja|紀州徳川家|qq=draft}}. In {{ill|Shōhō 2|ja|正保2nd year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|1645 AD|ja|1645th year|qq=draft}}), the temple was designated as a branch temple under {{ill|Takashitsu-in|ja|高室院|qq=draft}} on {{ill|Mount Kōya|ja|高野山|qq=draft}}, overseeing 11 sub-temples in the present-day Hashimoto area. Another temple was added to its jurisdiction in {{ill|Tenmei 4|ja|天明4th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|1784 AD|ja|1784th year|qq=draft}}).<ref name="temple_history"/>

In {{ill|Shōhō 5|ja|正保5th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|1648 AD|ja|1648th year|qq=draft}}), {{ill|Tokugawa Yorinobu|ja|徳川頼宣|qq=draft}} restored the temple buildings.<ref name="temple_history"/> He also granted the temple 2 *chōbu* (町歩) of farmland to cover the costs of worship and offerings for the principal image. Yorinobu visited the temple 11 times, and from then on, successive lords of the Kishū Domain and their retainers made frequent pilgrimages.<ref name="temple_history"/>

== Temple Grounds ==

* Main Hall (本堂)
* Kuri (庫裏) - Temple living quarters
* Mizuko Jizō Hall (水子地蔵堂)
* Bell Tower (鐘楼)
* Wisteria Garden (藤の庭)
* Mountain Gate (山門) - Two-story Nagaya-mon (長屋門)

