'''Koyasu Jizō-ji''' (子安地蔵寺) is a {{ill|Shingon Buddhist temple|ja|寺院|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shingon Buddhist temple|qq=}} of the {{ill|Kōyasan Shingon-shū|ja|高野山真言宗|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōyasan Shingon-shū|qq=}} sect, located in {{ill|Hashimoto, Wakayama|ja|和歌山県橋本市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hashimoto, Wakayama|qq=}}. Its {{ill|Mountain name (sangō)|ja|山号|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mountain name (sangō)|qq=}} is *Isan-zan* (易産山), and its principal image is {{ill|Jizō Bosatsu|ja|地蔵菩薩|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jizō Bosatsu|qq=}}. The temple’s formal name is *Isan-zan Gokoku-in Jizō-ji* (易産山護国院地蔵寺), while *Koyasu Jizō-ji* is a commonly used name. It is well known for its wisteria flowers.

== History ==

The temple was founded in the spring of {{ill|Tenpyō 9|ja|天平9年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpyō 9|qq=}} ({{ill|737 AD|ja|737年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/737 AD|qq=}}) by {{ill|Gyōki|ja|行基|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gyōki|qq=}}. The temple’s principal image, a statue of {{ill|Jizō Bosatsu|ja|地蔵菩薩|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jizō Bosatsu|qq=}}, is said to have been carved by Gyōki himself and is known as the "Most Victorious and Oldest Jizō Bosatsu in Japan." This Jizō was enshrined at the temple to provide prayers for safe childbirth, leading to its name *Koyasu Jizō* (子安地蔵).<ref name="temple_history">[https://hananotera.com/history History of Koyasu Jizō-ji]</ref>

In {{ill|Tenshō 9|ja|天正9年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō 9|qq=}} ({{ill|1581 AD|ja|1581年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1581 AD|qq=}}), during the {{ill|Kōyasan Campaign|ja|高野山攻め|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōyasan Campaign|qq=}} led by {{ill|Oda Nobunaga|ja|織田信長|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oda Nobunaga|qq=}} and his son {{ill|Oda Nobutaka|ja|織田信孝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oda Nobutaka|qq=}}, the temple was set ablaze, and all its structures were destroyed. However, the principal image was hidden deep in the mountains and later discovered by villagers. The location where it was hidden is still known today as *Kakuregata* (かくれがた).<ref name="temple_history"/>

During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}, the temple gained significant patronage from {{ill|Tokugawa Yorinobu|ja|徳川頼宣|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa Yorinobu|qq=}}, lord of the {{ill|Kishū Domain|ja|紀州藩|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kishū Domain|qq=}}, after it was said to have helped his daughter through a difficult childbirth. Koyasu Jizō-ji subsequently became the official prayer temple for safe childbirth for the {{ill|Kishū Tokugawa family|ja|紀州徳川家|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kishū Tokugawa family|qq=}}. In {{ill|Shōhō 2|ja|正保2年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōhō 2|qq=}} ({{ill|1645 AD|ja|1645年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1645 AD|qq=}}), the temple was designated as a branch temple under {{ill|Takashitsu-in|ja|高室院|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takashitsu-in|qq=}} on {{ill|Mount Kōya|ja|高野山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Kōya|qq=}}, overseeing 11 sub-temples in the present-day Hashimoto area. Another temple was added to its jurisdiction in {{ill|Tenmei 4|ja|天明4年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenmei 4|qq=}} ({{ill|1784 AD|ja|1784年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1784 AD|qq=}}).<ref name="temple_history"/>

In {{ill|Shōhō 5|ja|正保5年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōhō 5|qq=}} ({{ill|1648 AD|ja|1648年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1648 AD|qq=}}), {{ill|Tokugawa Yorinobu|ja|徳川頼宣|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa Yorinobu|qq=}} restored the temple buildings.<ref name="temple_history"/> He also granted the temple 2 *chōbu* (町歩) of farmland to cover the costs of worship and offerings for the principal image. Yorinobu visited the temple 11 times, and from then on, successive lords of the Kishū Domain and their retainers made frequent pilgrimages.<ref name="temple_history"/>

== Temple Grounds ==

* Main Hall (本堂)
* Kuri (庫裏) - Temple living quarters
* Mizuko Jizō Hall (水子地蔵堂)
* Bell Tower (鐘楼)
* Wisteria Garden (藤の庭)
* Mountain Gate (山門) - Two-story Nagaya-mon (長屋門)

